# C# Coding Standards

- Always use primary constructors for new classes where the language and framework allow it.
- Keep each class and interface in its own separate file.
- Prefer current .NET 10 and C# language features when implementing new code.
- Favor performant implementations, especially in hot paths, loops, IO, parsing, and database access.
- Apply SOLID and DRY principles where they improve clarity and maintainability.
- Add comments that explain what non-obvious code does and why it exists.
